                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I recently had an interesting experience, and I need your help.
<br />

<br />
I went to egypt, to explore one of those pyramids, when I found this odd looking door. After carefully opening it, and traveling down the dark, damp hallway, I came to this big room.
<br />

<br />
The room was dimly lighted, by a big metallic mirror at the base of a long air shaft. The walls were covered in egyptian writting, and at the opposite side of the room from where I entered, was a doorway. Next to this doorway, was a very lifelike statue of a sleeping griffon.
<br />

<br />
As I approached the door, and the griffon, I was startled when the griffon stood up, and faced me. It was several feet taller than myself, and his claws and beak looked very sharp and dangerous. What startled me more, was it began speaking to me.
<br />

<br />
Griffon: Beyond this door, lies the answers to every question about life, and the universe. I have been in charge of guarding this great knowledge for thousands upon thousands of years, though you are the first I've seen in many centuries. If you answer my riddle, I will let you pass. If you fail to answer correctly, however, you will become the first thing I've had the priviledge of eating in a very, very long time.
<br />

<br />
Me: uh.. I am sorry to disturb you, I don't need to pass. Mind if I leave back the way I came?
<br />

<br />
Grif: I don't think so, young man. I am very hungry. If you choose not to participate, then the rules set forth by my rulers don't apply, and I get to show you how sharp a griffon's talons truly are. Would you like to decline from participation? Please, let me just eat you now and avoid this game of riddle and answer.
<br />

<br />
It was during this part of the conversation, when I started to creep towards the door where I entered, but the griffon put his claw down, and dug an inch into the solid stone floor, as if it were soft cheese. I was too terrified to move.
<br />

<br />
Me: Oh, no. Nevermind my earlier request. Please ask your riddle. It may at least buy me a few minutes.
<br />

<br />
Grif: Ok, the riddle given to me, by my rulers, centuries ago, is this. What walks on four legs in the morning, two legs in the afternoon, and three legs in the evening? Do you wish to give now, and let me eat you, or shall we play this game? I'll only give you fifteen minutes to come up with an answer, as I grow very hungry.
<br />

<br />
Me: That's an easy one, and I won't need fifteen minutes. (*sigh of relief*) The answer is Man. He crawls on all fours during the morning of his life, as a child, He walks upright on two legs during the afternoon, or prime of his life, and He walks with a cane, in the evening, or declining years of his life.
<br />

<br />
Grif: Damn it! Figgures I would get a genius, after centuries of waiting. The rules say I must let you pass. How did you know, might I ask, the answer to that riddle?
<br />

<br />
Me: Everyone who's ever watched a saturday morning cartoon knows the answer to that riddle. It's very common knowledge. You would be very hard pressed to find someone who doesn't know it.
<br />

<br />
Grif: Saturday morning car.. toon?
<br />

<br />
Me: Long story, sufficient to say, a lot of people have heard this riddle before.
<br />

<br />
Grif: Then I shall go very hungry, for that is the only riddle ever given to me. It was the ultimate riddle, to wich only the smartest would figgure out. I feel I am quite useless at this point, and shall never eat again. I want so much to get to claw someone apart too. I havn't done that in quite some time, you know.
<br />

<br />
Me: Not all is lost, all you really need is a new riddle.
<br />

<br />
Grif: A new riddle? Why didn't I think of that. But I am so terrible at comming up with things like that. All I know is clawing, and eating, and tearing, not thinking of riddles. I am a griffon, you know. Not terribly bright, but very loyal.
<br />

<br />
Me: That's ok, I am sure I could come up with one for you.
<br />

<br />
Grif: Would you? That would be great! Although, I seem to remember there was a rule to the riddle as well. It's been a long time that I've used that same riddle, let's see if I can remember the rule that my rulers used when comming up with that one.
<br />

<br />
Grif: Ah yess, I remember now. The riddle, and the answer must not contain any words, phrases, or be about something that only a handfull of specialized people would know. Such as medical terms, or terms to describe objects that only people who used those objects would know. Everyone must have an equal, if little, chance at comming up with the answer.
<br />

<br />
Me: What about ryming? does it have to ryme?
<br />

<br />
Grif: No.. it doens't have to ryme, but I do like rymes and poems, so It should be poetic at least. I'll allow some leaway there.
<br />

<br />
Me: *thinking at this point* The unfortunate part is, I am not very good at comming up with riddles either. I do know a couple.. but..
<br />

<br />
Grif: Well, Try them out on me. Maybe one of those you know will work.
<br />

<br />
Me: There is this one. Take one off, and scratch it's head. What once was red is black instead.
<br />

<br />
Grif: Wow, that's a good one. I have no idea. What is the answer?
<br />

<br />
Me: A match.
<br />

<br />
Grif: A what? Nevermind, it doesn't matter. Does everyone worldwide know what a .. match.. is?
<br />

<br />
Me: Yes.. but I think most people know that riddle too. It was in a movie, a couple years back.
<br />

<br />
Grif: What's a Movie?
<br />

<br />
Me: Long story, but let's just say, a lot of people have heard it, and the other riddles that I know off hand, were in the same movie, so a lot of people will know them as well.
<br />

<br />
Grif: Well, that's not gonna help me much. I need something original. Something that most people havn't heard before. That no one has heard before, if possible.
<br />

<br />
Me: Well, that may take some time. Do you mind if I return with it, later?
<br />

<br />
Grif: Sure, take your time. It may be a while before I see another visitor anyway.
<br />

<br />
And with that I said my goodbyes, and left, to return to the real world.
<br />

<br />
Now you know my dilema. I must find a good riddle. The one rule is that it can't be any medical terms, or anything that most people won't know simply because they arn't in a certain proffesion, or don't use a certain item. That includes most computer terms, especially ones related only to certain online activities. It should ryme, but doesn't have to, as long as it sounds mysterious, or poetic in some fasion.
<br />

<br />
Have any of you, good riddles that I might pass along to him? He is getting quite hungry.
<br />

<br />
-
<br />
Morpheaous Mindtap
<br />
That Magus is useless!! I sat there for four hours saying 'Disneyland' and he never done a thing. The moment, however, I tell him to NOT send me to east commonlands, I find myself standing face to face with a shady swashbuckler!!!</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
