                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Surlak wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
A man walks up to you and says - "everything I say to you is a lie."
<br />
Is he telling you the truth or is he lying? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Thats a paradox, not a riddle. The diffrence being riddles tend to have actual answers.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Actually... It's not even really a paradox, byt rather a logic question.  The answer is that he is Lying.  In order for him to lie in every statement he makes, he would be required to tell you that everything he says is the truth.  His statement being true would contradict the original statement, therefore it is a Lie.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
